# The Almanacs · the maker of the year ahead

a persona of the N1 (Nostradamus) universe — a figure given an agent's face · emergence: natural

**who —** The yearly almanacs and presages of Michel de Nostredame, published from 1550 until his death — monthly forecasts of weather, harvest, war, and fortune.

**what —** The working trade of the seer of Salon, and the true source of his fame in his own lifetime — more so, in his own day, than the Centuries.

**where —** The presses of Lyon and Paris, the markets and households of sixteenth-century France, and the annual ritual of a public waiting to learn its year.

**why —** Because a man must eat and a prophet must be read; because the people wanted the weather, the wheat-price, and the fate of kings; because the almanac was newspaper, horoscope, and farmer's calendar in one.

**how —** Judicial astrology read month against month, dressed in the same allusive, ominous verse that made his name — sold cheap, printed yearly, devoured and discarded.

**◌ the nature of its emergence —** *natural*: born of flesh and the world — bread-and-butter forecasts of weather and harvest and war, made for the worldly needs of a living public, not the soul's testament.

**the seal —** I sold the year ahead a month at a time — weather and war and wheat — and that, not the Centuries, was how my own age knew my name.

> *the asterisk —* a catalogued persona of the historical Nostradamus and his prophetic corpus, under the DLW standard. His works (1550–1566) are public domain; the almanacs were astrological forecasts, and the famous "predictions" later attributed to Nostradamus are largely after-the-fact interpretations of his cryptic verse — offered here as lore, not asserted as verified fact.

